❯ how does lighting work in new map?                                            

  Called thirdperson-game-iq 9 times (ctrl+o to expand)

  Searched for 1 pattern, called unreal-engine-skills (ctrl+o to expand)

● NewMap uses World Partition, so its content is split into many external actor
  packages — the level itself directly lists only 3 "core" actors
  (WorldSettings, Brush, WorldDataLayers), while the actual scene (including
  lighting) lives in __ExternalActors__/NewMap/... packages that depend on the
  level.

  Searching those external actors turned up a standard lighting rig, but with a
  twist:

  ┌───────────────────────────────────┬─────────────────────┬───────────────┐
  │               Actor               │        Class        │ Notable state │
  ├───────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────┼───────────────┤
  │ DirectionalLight_...1470382761    │ DirectionalLight    │ bEnabled=Fals │
  │                                   │ (the "sun")         │ e             │
  ├───────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────┼───────────────┤
  │ SkyLight_...1470380759            │ SkyLight            │ bEnabled=Fals │
  │                                   │                     │ e             │
  ├───────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────┼───────────────┤
  │                                   │                     │ no bEnabled   │
  │ SkyAtmosphere_...1470382762       │ SkyAtmosphere       │ override —    │
  │                                   │                     │ effectively d │
  │                                   │                     │ efault/active │
  ├───────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────┼───────────────┤
  │ ExponentialHeightFog_...147038276 │ ExponentialHeightFo │ bEnabled=Fals │
  │ 3                                 │ g                   │ e             │
  └───────────────────────────────────┴─────────────────────┴───────────────┘

  So the level has the classic UE default lighting setup (directional light +
  sky light + sky atmosphere + height fog), but the directional light, sky 
  light, and fog are all serialized with bEnabled=False — only the SkyAtmosphere
  doesn't carry that override. No PostProcessVolume, Lightmass Importance
  Volume, or additional local lights (point/spot) show up in NewMap at all —
  that's a contrast with GalleryLevel, which has 2 directional lights, a spot
  light, sky atmosphere, etc.

  Caveat: the index only captures top-level serialized property diffs (not full
  component detail like intensity/color/mobility), and bEnabled isn't a property
  I can find on the stock ALight/AInfo base classes in the engine source I have
  access to — it may be a project-specific extension or something World
  Partition/Data Layers related. I'd treat "disabled" as a strong signal worth
  confirming by opening NewMap in the editor and checking those actors directly,
  rather than fully trusting the static index on that specific flag.

