❯ how does player input work in the game?                                       

  Called thirdperson-game-iq 2 times (ctrl+o to expand)

● Found it — BP_ThirdPersonCharacter is the actual player character for this
  project. Let me pull its full detail and event graph.

  Searched for 2 patterns, called thirdperson-game-iq 7 times (ctrl+o to expand)
● Confirmed — BP_ThirdPersonPlayerController::EventGraph calls AddMappingContext
  (via EnhancedInputLocalPlayerSubsystem) on IMC_Default at BeginPlay. Let me
  pull that full EventGraph to see the exact flow.

  Called thirdperson-game-iq 3 times (ctrl+o to expand)

● Now I have the full picture. Player input in this project uses Unreal's 
  Enhanced Input system, standard for the UE5 ThirdPerson template plus a couple
  of custom additions.

  Setup (BP_ThirdPersonPlayerController::EventGraph, on BeginPlay):
  - Waits a tick, checks IsLocalPlayerController, then grabs the
  EnhancedInputLocalPlayerSubsystem and calls AddMappingContext(IMC_Default, 
  Priority=0) — this activates the base action set (Move, Look, Jump, etc.).
  - Branches on Should Use Touch Controls: if true, spawns and adds the
  touch-controls widget to the player screen; if false (mouse/keyboard/gamepad),
  it also adds IMC_MouseLook as a second mapping context.

  Input actions (/Game/Input/Actions/): IA_Move (Axis2D), IA_Look, IA_MouseLook,
  IA_Jump, IA_DoubleJump, IA_Sprint — all mapped in IMC_Default
  (/Game/Input/IMC_Default), and referenced/consumed by BP_ThirdPersonCharacter.

  Character response (BP_ThirdPersonCharacter):
  - Move(X, Y) → AddMovementInput along GetForwardVector/GetRightVector derived
  from the controller's yaw rotation (standard camera-relative movement).
  - Aim(X, Y) → AddControllerYawInput / AddControllerPitchInput
  (camera/character look).
  - DoubleJump → a custom function: LaunchCharacter with Z = JumpZVelocity * √2,
  giving an extra vertical boost on top of the normal jump.
  - Touch-specific events also exist directly in the character's EventGraph:
  Event Touch Jump Start/End call Jump/StopJumping, and Primary/Secondary 
  Thumbstick events feed into the same Move/Aim functions — so touch input
  reuses the same movement/look logic as Enhanced Input.

  Note: the actual IA_* → Move/Aim/DoubleJump action bindings (the BindAction
  calls) aren't visible in the Blueprint graphs — they're almost certainly wired
  up in a native C++ base class (SetupPlayerInputComponent) that
  BP_ThirdPersonCharacter extends, which is standard for the UE5 C++ ThirdPerson
  template. That C++ source isn't part of this repo/index (this repo only holds
  the GameIQ tool), so I can't show you the exact BindAction lines — only that
  the Blueprint-side Move/Aim/DoubleJump functions are the landing points those
  bindings call into.

